TASK 6.5-FIX3: Hide reasoning LLM call from streaming events
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

CRITICAL CONSTRAINT
- Only touch:
    app/workflows/shared/reasoning_addon.py
    app/controllers/chat_controller.py
- Do NOT modify node bodies, intent.py, graph.py, state.py, routes.

PROBLEM
Event stream shows:
  chunk1: "Your three new tasks are now ready i"   <- LLM stream piece
  chunk2: "<full summary including reasoning>"      <- static node return
  chunk3: "n your list."                             <- LLM stream piece

The reasoning LLM call inside add_reasoning is being intercepted by
LangGraph's event system and streamed to the controller, while the
final node return also includes the same reasoning. Result: split,
interleaved output. Non-streaming LLM didn't help because LangGraph
emits on_chat_model_stream events even when streaming=False on the
LLM client side.

FIX (two parts)

PART A — Tag the reasoning call in reasoning_addon.py
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
In app/workflows/shared/reasoning_addon.py, change:
    response = llm.invoke(prompt)
To:
    response = llm.invoke(
        prompt,
        config={"tags": ["reasoning_addon"], "run_name": "reasoning_addon"}
    )

This tags every chat-model-stream event generated by this call with
"reasoning_addon" so the controller can identify and ignore them.

PART B — Filter tagged events in chat_controller.py
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
In app/controllers/chat_controller.py, locate the
on_chat_model_stream event handler in BOTH:
  - stream_chat_with_orchestrator
  - stream_chat_with_file

At the very top of the on_chat_model_stream branch (inside the
`if event_kind == "on_chat_model_stream":` block, before any chunk
processing), add:

    # Filter out events from internal-only LLM calls
    # (e.g. reasoning addon — these are appended by the node return,
    #  not meant to be streamed).
    tags = event.get("tags") or []
    if "reasoning_addon" in tags:
        continue

This skips chunk events tagged with "reasoning_addon" so they don't
appear as standalone chunks. The reasoning still shows up — but only
once, in the static node return after the deterministic message.

NOTE: LangGraph's astream_events v1 puts tags on the event itself.
If for some reason tags aren't propagated to the event dict, check
event["data"].get("tags") or event.get("metadata", {}).get("tags").
Inspect the event structure at runtime if needed and adapt.

